        "INDIAN market suggestion": "Based on current Indian dairy trends and research, here are specific modifications to optimize AI Livestock Monitoring for the Indian market:  - Technical Adaptation: Shift from expensive wearable sensors to an image-first AI architecture, like Gau Swastha, which uses a single side-angle photograph to screen for diseases and assess health without requiring hardware costs.\n  - Delivery Channel: Prioritize a WhatsApp-based chatbot or lightweight app like \"Sarlaben\" to provide instant feedback on cattle health, pregnancy, and milk production, bypassing rural connectivity and hardware limitations.\n  - Strategic Focus: Target the \"Bovine\" segment (cows and buffaloes) as it is the largest and most lucrative livestock category in India, focusing on detection for prevalent issues like mastitis, estrus cycles, and heat stress.\n  - Frugal Hardware: Use low-cost, repurposed smartphones in \"health scan stations\" or mobile-based facial recognition to eliminate the need for traditional tags or collars which cost approximately 25,000 INR per animal.\n  - Sustainable Features: Integrate personalized feed recommendations and scientific nutrition programs to help small-scale farmers optimize yield while reducing methane emissions and antibiotic use.\n  - Government Alignment: Leverage the Animal Husbandry Infrastructure Development Fund (AHIDF) and partnerships with cooperatives like Amul to ensure data sovereignty and reach the millions of smallholder farmers in remote regions.",
