        "INDIAN market suggestion": "Based on current Indian conservation trends and research, here are specific modifications to optimize AI Wildlife Conservation for the Indian market:  - Technical Adaptation: Focus on Edge AI and lightweight models that can run on low-cost TrailGuard AI camera traps or repurposed smartphones, ensuring functionality in remote regions like the Western Ghats or Himalayan foothills with limited connectivity.\n  - Strategic Focus: Prioritize the \"Big Five\" of Indian conservation\u2014Tigers, Elephants, Rhinos, Leopards, and Asiatic Lions\u2014while expanding acoustic libraries for endemic birds in biodiversity hotspots to improve representation in global databases like BirdNET.\n  - Human-Wildlife Conflict (HWC) Mitigation: Implement real-time \"Tiger/Elephant Alerts\" via WhatsApp or SMS to local livestock operators and \"Karta\" (heads of households) in forest-fringe communities to prevent retaliatory killings and ensure village safety.\n  - Community-Led Monitoring: Integrate with popular citizen science platforms like the India Biodiversity Portal or iNaturalist to gamify data collection, allowing rural youth and \"Eco-vanguard\" groups to upload sightings and report illegal activities.\n  - Government & Institutional Alignment: Ensure data compatibility with the National Tiger Conservation Authority (NTCA) and the M-STrIPES app to facilitate seamless integration with official forest department patrolling and census workflows.\n  - Frugal Infrastructure: Deploy solar-powered acoustic sensors (using recycled handsets) in high-canopy areas to detect chainsaw frequencies or gunshots, providing a low-cost alternative to expensive satellite-based monitoring for state forest departments.",
