        "INDIAN market suggestion": "Based on current Indian safety regulations and industrial trends, here are specific modifications to optimize AI Fatigue Detection for the Indian market:  - Regulatory Compliance: Align the system with the Ministry of Road Transport and Highways (MoRTH) AIS-184 standards, which mandate Driver Drowsiness and Attention Warning Systems (DDAWS) for all new commercial vehicles (M2, M3, N2, N3) starting April 2026.\n  - Edge-First Architecture: Implement vision-based analysis on the edge to ensure real-time alerts without dependency on cloud connectivity, essential for long-haul fleets navigating India's remote highways and variable network conditions.\n  - Technical Robustness: Utilize Percentage of Eyelid Closure (PERCLOS) and blink frequency algorithms trained on diverse Indian datasets to maintain accuracy across challenging local lighting, dust, and drivers wearing traditional headgear or sunglasses.\n  - Hardware Optimization: Integrate with existing vehicle telematics and Bharat Stage VI (BS-VI) electronic architectures to provide a unified safety dashboard for fleet managers, reducing the cost and complexity of secondary installations.\n  - Multi-Modal Monitoring: Incorporate non-intrusive sensors like steering wheel pressure or grip monitoring to complement vision-based systems, helping to differentiate between true fatigue and normal driving habits in complex Indian traffic.\n  - Cultural and Language Support: Deliver immediate in-cab audio alerts in regional languages (e.g., Hindi, Tamil, Telugu) and integrate with WhatsApp for real-time supervisor notifications and automated driver coaching logs.",
