        "INDIAN market suggestion": "Based on current Indian pharmaceutical trends and regulatory updates, here are specific modifications to optimize AI Drug Testing Automation for the Indian market:  - Regulatory Compliance: Align the AI model with the 2023 amendment to the New Drugs and Clinical Trial Rules, which officially authorizes and encourages non-animal and human-relevant testing methods like 3D organoids and advanced computational models.\n  - Classification Adherence: Ensure the software is developed to meet Class C medical device standards under the Central Drugs Standard Control Organisation (CDSCO) framework, which now mandates specific manufacturing or import licenses for AI diagnostic and testing tools.\n  - Dataset Localization: Validate the AI models using diverse Indian patient population datasets to account for regional genetic variations, as Indian regulators are increasingly skeptical of models trained exclusively on foreign datasets.\n  - Administrative Streamlining: Integrate generative AI features specifically designed to automate the preparation of Common Technical Documents (CTD) and dossiers to reduce rework caused by documentation gaps, aligning with the \"India AI\" mission to accelerate drug approval timelines.\n  - Testing Phase-Out Support: Focus the automation on replacing traditional animal experimentation with in-silico and AI-driven predictive models, positioning the startup to benefit from proposed unified funding platforms via DBT and BIRAC.\n  - Operational Speed: Optimize workflows to meet the new 45-day statutory processing timeline proposed by the Health Ministry, moving away from the previous 90-day system to support faster \"Bioavailability/Bioequivalence\" (BA/BE) studies.",
