        "LANGUAGE LOCALIZATION": "Recommended languages  - Hindi: Essential for broad accessibility among the aging population and caregivers in North India (Bharat).\n  - Tamil: Important for the mature healthcare and geriatric care markets in Southern India.\n  - Bengali: Critical for reaching the high density of elderly residents in West Bengal and major urban hubs.Critical surfaces to localize  - UX and Voice Interface: Audio-guided exercise prompts and navigation to accommodate elderly users with low digital literacy.\n  - Content: Rehabilitation exercises, safety warnings, and medical instructions must use common regional terms.\n  - Onboarding: Simple, vernacular video tutorials to explain how to use the AI motion tracking.\n  - Support: WhatsApp-integrated customer service for family members and patients in their preferred language.Biggest localization risks  - Medical Terminology: Complex anatomical or clinical terms may not translate well, requiring simplified layman's language to ensure patient safety.\n  - Dialect Sensitivity: Variations in how symptoms or pain are described can lead to \"trust gaps\" if the AI appears too robotic or formal.\n  - Behavioral Adoption: English-only interfaces are often perceived as \"too complex,\" leading to high drop-off rates among the primary patient demographic.3-month pilot plan  - Launch a bilingual (English/Hindi) MVP focusing on core physical therapy exercises\n  - Develop localized \"How-to\" video guides for patient onboarding in 3 languages\n  - Create a localized automated alert system (SMS/WhatsApp) for caregivers\n  - Partner with 3 regional clinics to test the clarity of translated exercise instructions and adjust based on patient feedback",
