        "LANGUAGE LOCALIZATION": "Recommended languages  - Hindi: Essential for broad adoption across North Indian design hubs and for general business communication in the SME sector.\n  - Kannada: Vital for the Bengaluru tech and design ecosystem, which serves as India's primary hub for startups and global capability centers.\n  - Tamil: Critical for the Chennai-based manufacturing and SaaS corridor where design documentation is integral to large-scale engineering and software projects.Critical surfaces to localize  - UX and Navigation: Menus and tooltips to ensure non-native English speakers can navigate complex documentation workflows.\n  - Onboarding and Support: Localized tutorials and \"how-to\" guides to reduce the learning curve for junior designers and business stakeholders.\n  - Marketing: Case studies and value propositions emphasizing local project success and compliance with Indian industry standards.Biggest localization risks  - Technical Jargon: Translation of specific design and engineering terms may lead to ambiguity if not carefully mapped to common industry usage.\n  - Collaboration Friction: Misalignment between localized documentation and English-centric design tools (like Figma or Adobe) could cause workflow bottlenecks.\n  - Trust Deficit: Inaccurate translations in legal or compliance-heavy documentation can lead to a perceived lack of professional rigor.3-month pilot plan  - Launch a bilingual (English/Hindi) MVP interface for core documentation features\n  - Develop localized onboarding video series in Hindi and Kannada for pilot users\n  - Establish a \"Hinglish\" (Hindi-English) glossary for technical design terms to ensure consistency\n  - Partner with 3 regional design agencies to validate the clarity of localized support documentation",
