        "LANGUAGE LOCALIZATION": "Recommended languages  - Hindi: Essential for reaching the massive low-income population in the North and Central Indian heartland.\n  - Tamil: Critical for accessing deep-tier health and education networks in a state with high literacy and digital penetration.\n  - Telugu: Vital for the large base of rural and semi-urban users in Andhra Pradesh and Telangana seeking upward mobility.Critical surfaces to localize  - UX and Navigation: Voice-first interface with large icons and local language labels to accommodate varying literacy levels.\n  - Expert Content: Core advice in health, nutrition, and education must be delivered in the user's primary tongue to ensure accuracy and trust.\n  - Onboarding: WhatsApp-integrated audio instructions in local dialects to guide users through the initial profiling.\n  - Support: Localized chatbots and human-in-the-loop escalation paths for complex queries.Biggest localization risks  - Translation Nuance: Medical and financial terminology may not have common equivalents, leading to dangerous misunderstandings.\n  - Trust Barrier: Users may perceive an English-only AI as elite or \"not for them,\" hindering the goal of universal access.\n  - Dialect Sensitivity: Standard versions of Hindi or Tamil may feel \"too formal,\" alienating users who speak colloquial regional variations.3-month pilot plan  - Launch a bilingual (English/Hindi) WhatsApp bot for the initial 50-user validation phase\n  - Develop a library of the 50 most common health and education queries translated into Hindi and Tamil\n  - Implement a voice-to-text input feature that recognizes Hinglish and regional dialects\n  - Recruit 5 local subject matter experts per language to audit and calibrate AI-generated advice for cultural relevance",
