        "LANGUAGE LOCALIZATION": "Recommended languages  - Hindi: Essential for reaching the massive student population in the \"Hindi heartland\" of Northern and Central India.\n  - Telugu: Critical for the high-demand education markets and \"coaching hub\" culture in Andhra Pradesh and Telangana.\n  - Tamil: Vital for the high-literacy and education-focused demographic in Tamil Nadu, which has a strong regional language preference.Critical surfaces to localize  - Content and Pedagogy: Explanations, analogies, and practice questions must be available in local languages to ensure conceptual clarity.\n  - UX and Navigation: Menu items and instructions should use simple regional terms to reduce cognitive load for younger learners.\n  - Support and Onboarding: Localized WhatsApp-based help and voice-enabled onboarding for parents who may not be fluent in English.\n  - Marketing: Advertisements focusing on regional success stories and value propositions tailored to local school board exams.Biggest localization risks  - Concept Nuance: Abstract scientific or mathematical concepts may lose accuracy if translated literally without pedagogical context.\n  - Script Rendering: Complex scripts like Telugu or Tamil can sometimes break on low-end mobile devices used by the target demographic.\n  - Dialect Gaps: Standard Hindi may feel too formal or \"textbook-like\" compared to the colloquial \"Hinglish\" or regional dialects students actually speak.3-month pilot plan  - Launch a bilingual (English + Hindi) MVP for a specific subject (e.g., Mathematics) to test engagement\n  - Develop a localized \"voice-to-query\" feature to allow students to ask questions in their native tongue\n  - Create localized micro-content (short videos or infographics) explaining 50 core concepts in Hindi and Telugu\n  - Establish a feedback loop with 50 students from Tier 2 cities to identify translation errors or cultural disconnects",
