        "LANGUAGE LOCALIZATION": "Recommended languages  - Hindi: Essential for broad accessibility across the large workforce in Northern and Central India (Bharat).\n  - Bengali: Critical for reaching the high-density corporate and industrial hubs in West Bengal and neighboring regions.\n  - Marathi: Necessary for the significant industrial and corporate sectors in Maharashtra, particularly Mumbai and Pune.Critical surfaces to localize  - UX and Navigation: Simple, intuitive interface with local language labels for non-English proficient employees.\n  - Reporting and Content: Diversity reports, data collection forms, and terminology must be available in local languages to ensure accurate self-reporting.\n  - Support and Onboarding: Localized training materials and helpdesk support to facilitate smooth adoption among a diverse workforce.\n  - Legal and Compliance: Consent managers and data protection disclosures must be presented in the user's preferred language to meet DPDP Act requirements.Biggest localization risks  - Data Accuracy: Misinterpretation of diversity-related terms in English could lead to incorrect data entry and skewed analytics.\n  - Trust and Participation: Employees may feel alienated or suspicious of an English-only tool, leading to low response rates for sensitive diversity surveys.\n  - Compliance Gaps: Failure to provide clear, localized consent forms may result in non-compliance with Indian data privacy regulations (DPDP Act).3-month pilot plan  - Develop a bilingual (English/Hindi) MVP for the core data collection and reporting interface\n  - Create localized \"Consent Manager\" modules in Hindi, Bengali, and Marathi to ensure legal compliance\n  - Implement a simplified, icon-driven UX for mobile-first employees with local language tooltips\n  - Conduct pilot testing with 2-3 regional offices to validate the clarity of translated diversity metrics and terminology",
